<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-700-020  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 700 020.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  July 23 1990 v9 n15 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DOD's financial organizations consolidated under Comptroller.andO;(Defense Department consolidates accounting, finance systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AccountingOrganization StructureReorganizationGovernment AgencyFinancial ServicesUnited States. Department of Defense.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DOD's Financial Organizations Consolidated Under ComptrollerandM;The Defense Department has consolidated the armed services' major accountingand finance organizations under the authority of the DOD comptroller, SeanO'Keefe.andM;Deputy Secretary Donald Atwood ordered the consolidation as part of thecontinuing Defense Management Review, which also called for consolidation ofall existing ADP centers and software design shops in DOD.andM;The finance consolidation will be carried out by a team of senior DefenseDepartment officials who will &quot;develop detailed organizational plans for thecontrol and direction of DOD accounting and finance policies, procedures,systems and operations,&quot; a Pentagon statement said.andM;Consolidated under O'Keefe will be the Army Finance and Accounting Center, inIndianapolis; Navy Accounting and Finance Center, Arlington, Va.; NavyFinance Center, Cleveland; Air Force Accounting and Finance Center, denver;Defense Logistics AGency Finance Center, Columbus, Ohio; and the WashingtonHeadquarters Services Finance and Accounting Operations in the Pentagon.andM;These centers operate the principal financial management systems for theservices and DLA.andP;  &quot;There is a great need within the department forstandardization for financial and accounting information,&quot; Atwood said.andP;  &quot;Theintegrated Defense finance and accounting organization will enable us to useour limited resources with greater efficiency.&quot;andM;The information systems that run at the centers support payroll and personnelfunctions and provide the information on which the services base theirfinancial statements to DOD and Congress.andP;  These statements often have beencriticized by outside auditors for being in error by billions of dollars.andM;In February, the General Accounting Office declare the Air Force&quot;unauditable&quot; because the service's 131 different accounting systems were&quot;incapable of providing...reliable information.&quot;andP;  Pentagon officials said GAOis performning a similar examination of Navy finance systems.andM;DOD announced no cost savings from the finance consolidation.andP;  recentlyannounced consolidations of inventory and maintenance centers will save $3.9billion over four years, Pentagon officials said.andM;Cynthia Kendall, the deputy comptroller for IRM, said during an interviewearlier this year that consolidations will occur in a several operationsareas including finance and accounting, ADP, inventory and maintenancecenters.andM;The aDP consolidation was scheduled for this month but has been delayed whilethe services prepare responses to a draft proposal that would reduce majorADP centers from more than 100 to 18.andM;Overall, DOD officials predict DMR-related consolidations will save $5billion.andO;</TEXT></DOC>